            <h1>A GUIDE TO LINUX</h1>
            <p>Linux began as a response to the proprietary nature of Unix. In 1983, <strong>Richard Stallman</strong> launched the <strong>GNU Project</strong> to create a free, Unix-like operating system, producing key tools and utilities. However, GNU lacked a core componentâ€”a functioning kernel.</p>
            <p>In 1991, <strong>Linus Torvalds</strong>, a Finnish student, developed the Linux kernel as a personal project to explore a free, Unix-compatible OS on his Intel PC. He shared it online, inviting collaboration, and Linux quickly attracted a global community of developers. Linux's open-source license allowed anyone to view, modify, and distribute the code, fostering rapid innovation.</p>
            <p>The combination of Torvalds' Linux kernel with GNU tools created a fully functional OS, commonly called <strong>GNU/Linux</strong>. It became popular in academic, business, and eventually consumer spaces. Today, Linux powers everything from servers and supercomputers to smartphones (through Android). Torvalds and contributors continue to improve Linux, making it one of the most reliable and adaptable OS options globally.</p>

            <h2>RESOURCES</h2>
            <p>Here are some key resources for learning about Linux, its history, and how to work with it effectively:</p>

            <ul>
                <li><strong>Books</strong>:
                    <ul>
                        <li>"The Linux Command Line" by William E. Shotts: A great introduction to the Linux command line.</li>
                        <li>"How Linux Works" by Brian Ward: Covers Linux's inner workings and is excellent for beginners.</li>
                        <li>"Linux Bible" by Christopher Negus: Comprehensive guide, covering various Linux distributions and practical use.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Websites & Tutorials</strong>:
                    <ul>
                        <li><a href="https://training.linuxfoundation.org/" target="_blank">Linux Foundation Training</a>: Offers free and paid Linux courses, including certifications.</li>
                        <li><a href="https://linuxjourney.com/" target="_blank">Linux Journey</a>: Free, interactive Linux learning platform with beginner to advanced topics.</li>
                        <li><a href="https://www.tldp.org/" target="_blank">The Linux Documentation Project</a>: Collection of free guides and how-tos.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Video Courses</strong>:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Udemy Linux for Beginners: Good starting point with hands-on exercises.</li>
                        <li><a href="https://www.edx.org/" target="_blank">EdX Linux Foundation's "Introduction to Linux"</a>: A free course that provides an extensive overview.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Community and Forums</strong>:
                    <ul>
                        <li><a href="https://www.linux.org/forums/" target="_blank">Linux.org Forum</a>: Friendly community to ask questions and discuss Linux.</li>
                        <li><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/linux/" target="_blank">Reddit (r/linux)</a>: Discussions, resources, and troubleshooting advice from experienced users.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
